  "prompt": "What is the best gaming PC I can get for 1400\u20ac?",
  "response": "As of the latest updates, building or purchasing a pre-built gaming PC for \u20ac1400 can get you a very capable machine that should handle most modern games at high settings. Here\u2019s a recommended build that balances performance and future-proofing:\n\n1. **CPU (Processor):**  \n   - **AMD Ryzen 5 5600X** or **Intel Core i5-12600K**: Both options offer strong performance in both gaming and productivity tasks. If you plan on doing a lot of multitasking or streaming, the Intel option may be preferable.\n\n2. **GPU (Graphics Card):**  \n   - **NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3060 Ti** or **AMD Radeon RX 6700 XT**: These GPUs are excellent for 1080p and 1440p gaming. They offer good value and solid performance, making them ideal for current games.\n\n3. **Motherboard:**  \n   - **B550 chipset (for Ryzen)** or **Z690 chipset (for Intel)**: Choose based on your CPU. Look for brands like ASUS, MSI, or Gigabyte with good reviews and features like Wi-Fi, M.2 slots for SSDs, and USB connectivity.\n\n4. **Memory (RAM):**  \n   - **16GB (2x8GB) DDR4-3200MHz or faster**: Brands like Corsair Vengeance or G.Skill Ripjaws are reliable options. If you can stretch your budget slightly, consider 32GB for extra future-proofing.\n\n5. **Storage:**  \n   - **1TB NVMe SSD**: Look for a drive with good read/write speeds such as the Samsung 970 EVO or Western Digital SN570. Consider adding a larger HDD if you need more space for media and less critical applications.\n\n6. **Power Supply (PSU):**  \n   - **600W to 750W 80 PLUS Gold certified**: Ensure it's from a reputable brand like Seasonic, Corsair, or EVGA for reliability and efficiency.\n\n7. **Case:**  \n   - Choose a mid-tower case that supports your GPU and has good airflow. Examples include the NZXT H510 or Phanteks P300A. Make sure it has enough space for future upgrades and good cable management features.\n\n8. **Cooling:**  \n   - Stock coolers are often adequate, especially for AMD CPUs, but consider a third-party air cooler or AIO liquid cooler (e.g., Cooler Master Hyper 212 or NZXT Kraken X53) for better thermal performance.\n\n9. **Operating System:**  \n   - Windows 11 might require a separate purchase unless you have an existing license or opt for Linux.\n\nRemember, prices and availability for PC components can fluctuate due to demand and supply chain issues. It\u2019s worth checking local retailers or e-commerce platforms for deals or potential bundle offers. Additionally, if you\u2019re building the PC yourself, make sure to factor in any necessary tools or new peripherals you might need within your budget.",
